1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,254
The government can take your home.

2
00:00:02,254 --> 00:00:05,260
Most people know that — for a highway,

3
00:00:05,260 --> 00:00:06,763
a school, a bridge.

4
00:00:06,763 --> 00:00:09,393
But what if it takes your home,

5
00:00:09,393 --> 00:00:12,023
in perfect condition, having done nothing wrong,

6
00:00:12,023 --> 00:00:15,029
and hands the land to a private developer?

7
00:00:15,029 --> 00:00:18,035
In 2005, a woman's small pink house in

8
00:00:18,035 --> 00:00:21,041
Connecticut put that exact question in front of

9
00:00:21,041 --> 00:00:22,543
the Supreme Court .

10
00:00:22,543 --> 00:00:25,549
The answer changed what two words in the

11
00:00:25,549 --> 00:00:27,428
Constitution are allowed to mean.

12
00:00:27,823 --> 00:00:30,229
The power is called eminent domain.

13
00:00:30,229 --> 00:00:33,037
The Fifth Amendment lets the government take

14
00:00:33,037 --> 00:00:36,245
private property — but only "for public use,"

15
00:00:36,245 --> 00:00:39,454
and only if it pays you a fair

16
00:00:39,454 --> 00:00:40,256
price .

17
00:00:40,256 --> 00:00:43,064
For most of history, "public use" meant

18
00:00:43,064 --> 00:00:45,871
something the public actually uses: a road,

19
00:00:45,871 --> 00:00:47,475
a reservoir, a courthouse.

20
00:00:47,475 --> 00:00:48,277
Kelo v.

21
00:00:48,277 --> 00:00:51,486
New London asked whether those two words could

22
00:00:51,486 --> 00:00:54,293
stretch to cover something else entirely —

23
00:00:54,293 --> 00:00:57,101
taking working-class homes and giving the land

24
00:00:57,101 --> 00:01:00,309
to private business in the hope of jobs

25
00:01:00,309 --> 00:01:01,112
and taxes.

26
00:01:01,112 --> 00:01:03,919
Over the next twelve minutes: the neighborhood

27
00:01:03,919 --> 00:01:07,127
that was erased, the 5-4 decision that allowed

28
00:01:07,127 --> 00:01:09,935
it, and the spectacular way it backfired.

29
00:01:10,330 --> 00:01:12,086
The place is New London,

30
00:01:12,086 --> 00:01:14,543
Connecticut, a small city on the water,

31
00:01:14,543 --> 00:01:17,001
and the neighborhood is called Fort Trumbull.

32
00:01:17,001 --> 00:01:19,809
It is not rich, but it is real

33
00:01:19,809 --> 00:01:22,618
— modest homes, some lived in for generations

34
00:01:22,618 --> 00:01:22,969
.

35
00:01:23,364 --> 00:01:25,971
One of them belongs to Susette Kelo.

36
00:01:25,971 --> 00:01:28,951
It is a small house she has fixed

37
00:01:28,951 --> 00:01:31,186
up and painted a distinctive pink,

38
00:01:31,186 --> 00:01:33,421
with a view of the water.

39
00:01:33,421 --> 00:01:35,283
She has done nothing wrong.

40
00:01:35,283 --> 00:01:37,145
Her home is not run-down.

41
00:01:37,145 --> 00:01:39,380
There is no crime scene here,

42
00:01:39,380 --> 00:01:41,615
no blight, no code violations .

43
00:01:42,010 --> 00:01:44,379
But the city has a plan.

44
00:01:44,379 --> 00:01:47,144
The pharmaceutical company Pfizer is building a

45
00:01:47,144 --> 00:01:49,908
large research facility nearby, and New London

46
00:01:49,908 --> 00:01:53,068
wants to capitalize on it — to remake

47
00:01:53,068 --> 00:01:55,832
the whole Fort Trumbull area with offices,

48
00:01:55,832 --> 00:01:58,992
a hotel, and upscale housing that would bring

49
00:01:58,992 --> 00:02:01,361
in jobs and tax revenue .

50
00:02:01,756 --> 00:02:04,491
To do it, the city works through a

51
00:02:04,491 --> 00:02:06,542
private nonprofit acting as its development

52
00:02:06,542 --> 00:02:08,593
agent, the New London Development Corporation.

53
00:02:08,593 --> 00:02:11,327
And that agency is given the power to

54
00:02:11,327 --> 00:02:14,062
do something dramatic: to use eminent domain to

55
00:02:14,062 --> 00:02:16,797
condemn the homes in Fort Trumbull — to

56
00:02:16,797 --> 00:02:18,506
force the owners to sell,

57
00:02:18,506 --> 00:02:20,899
whether they want to or not .

58
00:02:21,294 --> 00:02:24,136
Susette Kelo and a handful of neighbors refuse.

59
00:02:24,136 --> 00:02:26,978
They are not holding out for more money.

60
00:02:26,978 --> 00:02:29,820
They simply do not want to lose their

61
00:02:29,820 --> 00:02:32,662
homes so that someone else can build something

62
00:02:32,662 --> 00:02:34,439
more profitable on the land.

63
00:02:34,439 --> 00:02:36,926
So they sue, represented by a public-interest

64
00:02:36,926 --> 00:02:39,057
law firm, the Institute for Justice,

65
00:02:39,057 --> 00:02:41,899
and their fight climbs all the way to

66
00:02:41,899 --> 00:02:43,320
the Supreme Court .

67
00:02:43,716 --> 00:02:46,272
And the question they bring is deceptively

68
00:02:46,272 --> 00:02:46,637
simple.

69
00:02:46,637 --> 00:02:48,828
The Constitution allows takings "for public

70
00:02:48,828 --> 00:02:51,749
use." Is handing your home to a private

71
00:02:51,749 --> 00:02:54,670
developer — for a plan that might create

72
00:02:54,670 --> 00:02:56,861
jobs — really a "public use"?

73
00:02:56,861 --> 00:02:59,782
Or has the city just found a way

74
00:02:59,782 --> 00:03:02,704
to take from one private owner and give

75
00:03:02,704 --> 00:03:03,434
to another?

76
00:03:03,829 --> 00:03:06,297
To see why this was so hard,

77
00:03:06,297 --> 00:03:09,117
you have to look closely at the words

78
00:03:09,117 --> 00:03:10,175
themselves: "public use."

79
00:03:10,570 --> 00:03:13,371
Read narrowly, "public use" means the public

80
00:03:13,371 --> 00:03:16,572
gets to use the thing — you can

81
00:03:16,572 --> 00:03:19,773
drive on the road, drink from the reservoir,

82
00:03:19,773 --> 00:03:21,373
walk into the courthouse.

83
00:03:21,373 --> 00:03:24,574
Under that reading, taking homes to hand to

84
00:03:24,574 --> 00:03:27,775
a private company fails, because the public will

85
00:03:27,775 --> 00:03:30,976
not own or use the new development; private

86
00:03:30,976 --> 00:03:32,176
parties will .

87
00:03:32,572 --> 00:03:34,345
But over the twentieth century,

88
00:03:34,345 --> 00:03:37,183
courts had read those words more and more

89
00:03:37,183 --> 00:03:39,666
broadly — as "public purpose." Under that

90
00:03:39,666 --> 00:03:42,504
reading, a taking is fine as long as

91
00:03:42,504 --> 00:03:44,277
it serves some public benefit,

92
00:03:44,277 --> 00:03:47,115
even if a private party ends up with

93
00:03:47,115 --> 00:03:47,824
the property.

94
00:03:47,824 --> 00:03:49,598
Clearing genuine slums, for example,

95
00:03:49,598 --> 00:03:52,081
had been upheld on that logic .

96
00:03:52,476 --> 00:03:55,389
New London's argument leaned entirely on the

97
00:03:55,389 --> 00:03:56,221
broad reading.

98
00:03:56,221 --> 00:03:59,549
The city was not claiming Fort Trumbull was

99
00:03:59,549 --> 00:04:00,381
a slum.

100
00:04:00,381 --> 00:04:03,293
It was claiming that economic development itself

101
00:04:03,293 --> 00:04:05,374
— more jobs, more taxes,

102
00:04:05,374 --> 00:04:08,702
a revitalized waterfront — is a public purpose,

103
00:04:08,702 --> 00:04:11,198
and therefore a public use .

104
00:04:11,594 --> 00:04:13,572
If the Court accepted that,

105
00:04:13,572 --> 00:04:15,155
the implications were enormous.

106
00:04:15,155 --> 00:04:18,321
Almost any home, anywhere, could be taken and

107
00:04:18,321 --> 00:04:21,486
handed to a developer, as long as a

108
00:04:21,486 --> 00:04:24,652
city could claim the new use would generate

109
00:04:24,652 --> 00:04:27,422
more economic activity than the old one.

110
00:04:27,422 --> 00:04:30,588
A modest house almost always produces less tax

111
00:04:30,588 --> 00:04:32,962
revenue than offices or luxury condos.

112
00:04:32,962 --> 00:04:36,128
Under the broad reading, that gap alone could

113
00:04:36,128 --> 00:04:37,710
justify taking it .

114
00:04:38,106 --> 00:04:41,067
So the case was never really about one

115
00:04:41,067 --> 00:04:41,808
pink house.

116
00:04:41,808 --> 00:04:44,769
It was about whether the words "for public

117
00:04:44,769 --> 00:04:47,731
use" still set any limit at all on

118
00:04:47,731 --> 00:04:50,322
whose property the government can transfer to

119
00:04:50,322 --> 00:04:50,693
whom.

120
00:04:51,088 --> 00:04:53,992
In 2005, the Supreme Court sided with the

121
00:04:53,992 --> 00:04:54,356
city.

122
00:04:54,356 --> 00:04:56,897
By a vote of five to four,

123
00:04:56,897 --> 00:04:59,802
it held that taking the Fort Trumbull homes

124
00:04:59,802 --> 00:05:02,706
for the economic-development plan did count as a

125
00:05:02,706 --> 00:05:05,248
"public use" under the Fifth Amendment .

126
00:05:05,643 --> 00:05:08,805
The opinion was written by Justice John Paul

127
00:05:08,805 --> 00:05:09,200
Stevens.

128
00:05:09,200 --> 00:05:12,362
The Court did not say the homes had

129
00:05:12,362 --> 00:05:13,548
to be blighted.

130
00:05:13,548 --> 00:05:15,919
It said that a carefully considered

131
00:05:15,919 --> 00:05:17,895
economic-development plan, aimed at public

132
00:05:17,895 --> 00:05:19,871
benefits like jobs and revenue,

133
00:05:19,871 --> 00:05:23,033
qualifies as a public purpose — and that

134
00:05:23,033 --> 00:05:26,195
courts should largely defer to a city's judgment

135
00:05:26,195 --> 00:05:28,566
about what its community needs .

136
00:05:28,566 --> 00:05:30,543
"Public use," in other words,

137
00:05:30,543 --> 00:05:32,914
would be read as "public purpose."

138
00:05:33,309 --> 00:05:36,805
One vote in the majority came with a

139
00:05:36,805 --> 00:05:37,243
caveat.

140
00:05:37,243 --> 00:05:40,302
Justice Kennedy, who joined the Court's opinion,

141
00:05:40,302 --> 00:05:43,798
wrote separately to stress that a taking meant

142
00:05:43,798 --> 00:05:46,857
only to benefit a particular private party,

143
00:05:46,857 --> 00:05:49,479
with a merely pretextual public purpose,

144
00:05:49,479 --> 00:05:52,539
would still be unconstitutional — leaving a

145
00:05:52,539 --> 00:05:55,598
door, however narrow, for future challenges .

146
00:05:55,993 --> 00:05:57,919
The four dissenters were alarmed.

147
00:05:57,919 --> 00:06:00,616
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote the main

148
00:06:00,616 --> 00:06:02,928
dissent, and her warning was blunt.

149
00:06:02,928 --> 00:06:04,854
Under this ruling, she argued,

150
00:06:04,854 --> 00:06:07,936
the government could now take property from one

151
00:06:07,936 --> 00:06:11,019
private owner simply to give it to another

152
00:06:11,019 --> 00:06:13,330
who might use it more profitably.

153
00:06:13,330 --> 00:06:16,413
The specter, she wrote, was that any home

154
00:06:16,413 --> 00:06:19,495
could be taken for any other private use

155
00:06:19,495 --> 00:06:22,577
that promised more taxes — and that the

156
00:06:22,577 --> 00:06:24,503
words "for public use" had,

157
00:06:24,503 --> 00:06:27,585
in effect, been erased from the Constitution .

158
00:06:27,585 --> 00:06:30,282
Justice Thomas wrote a separate dissent arguing

159
00:06:30,282 --> 00:06:33,365
the Court had drifted far from the original

160
00:06:33,365 --> 00:06:34,906
meaning of the clause.

161
00:06:35,301 --> 00:06:37,297
It was a 5-4 split,

162
00:06:37,297 --> 00:06:39,293
and unlike many such splits,

163
00:06:39,293 --> 00:06:42,487
it did not fall along the usual lines.

164
00:06:42,487 --> 00:06:45,680
That is part of why what happened next

165
00:06:45,680 --> 00:06:46,878
was so unusual.

166
00:06:46,878 --> 00:06:49,672
Because the public reaction to Kelo did

167
00:06:49,672 --> 00:06:52,068
something American legal decisions almost never

168
00:06:52,068 --> 00:06:54,862
do: it united nearly everyone against it.

169
00:06:55,257 --> 00:06:58,212
The ruling set off one of the largest

170
00:06:58,212 --> 00:07:00,797
popular backlashes to any modern Supreme Court

171
00:07:00,797 --> 00:07:03,382
decision — and a rare bipartisan one.

172
00:07:03,382 --> 00:07:05,967
People across the political spectrum recoiled at

173
00:07:05,967 --> 00:07:08,921
the idea that the government could bulldoze your

174
00:07:08,921 --> 00:07:11,876
home to make way for a more profitable

175
00:07:11,876 --> 00:07:12,984
private project .

176
00:07:13,379 --> 00:07:14,675
And legislatures responded.

177
00:07:14,675 --> 00:07:16,835
In the years after Kelo,

178
00:07:16,835 --> 00:07:19,426
by the Institute for Justice's count,

179
00:07:19,426 --> 00:07:22,882
roughly forty or more states passed new laws

180
00:07:22,882 --> 00:07:25,474
or constitutional amendments restricting the use

181
00:07:25,474 --> 00:07:28,066
of eminent domain for economic development.

182
00:07:28,066 --> 00:07:31,521
The catch — and it is an important

183
00:07:31,521 --> 00:07:34,977
one — is that many of these reforms

184
00:07:34,977 --> 00:07:37,137
were later criticized as weak,

185
00:07:37,137 --> 00:07:40,593
full of loopholes that left the core power

186
00:07:40,593 --> 00:07:41,457
largely intact.

187
00:07:41,457 --> 00:07:44,912
"Passed a reform" did not always mean "actually

188
00:07:44,912 --> 00:07:46,208
protected homeowners" .

189
00:07:46,603 --> 00:07:50,186
But the sharpest verdict on Kelo came not

190
00:07:50,186 --> 00:07:51,530
from a legislature.

191
00:07:51,530 --> 00:07:54,217
It came from the land itself.

192
00:07:54,217 --> 00:07:57,800
After the homes of Fort Trumbull were taken

193
00:07:57,800 --> 00:08:00,487
and demolished, the grand redevelopment was

194
00:08:00,487 --> 00:08:01,383
never built.

195
00:08:01,383 --> 00:08:04,966
The promised offices and hotel did not appear.

196
00:08:04,966 --> 00:08:07,205
The cleared land sat empty,

197
00:08:07,205 --> 00:08:08,997
year after year .

198
00:08:09,392 --> 00:08:11,255
And then the final irony.

199
00:08:11,255 --> 00:08:14,237
In 2009, Pfizer — the company whose arrival

200
00:08:14,237 --> 00:08:17,218
had justified the whole plan — closed its

201
00:08:17,218 --> 00:08:19,454
New London facility and left .

202
00:08:19,454 --> 00:08:22,063
The neighborhood had been erased for a

203
00:08:22,063 --> 00:08:25,044
development that never came, to serve a company

204
00:08:25,044 --> 00:08:26,535
that did not stay.

205
00:08:26,535 --> 00:08:29,516
For a long time, the most famous use

206
00:08:29,516 --> 00:08:32,497
of the bulldozed land was as a place

207
00:08:32,497 --> 00:08:33,988
to dump storm debris.

208
00:08:34,383 --> 00:08:37,178
And it is worth being precise about what

209
00:08:37,178 --> 00:08:39,973
"taken" meant for the people who lived there.

210
00:08:39,973 --> 00:08:42,769
Some families had been in Fort Trumbull for

211
00:08:42,769 --> 00:08:43,118
generations.

212
00:08:43,118 --> 00:08:45,913
They were paid the market value of their

213
00:08:45,913 --> 00:08:48,708
homes, as the Constitution requires — but market

214
00:08:48,708 --> 00:08:51,504
value does not buy back the place you

215
00:08:51,504 --> 00:08:53,251
have lived your whole life,

216
00:08:53,251 --> 00:08:56,046
or the neighbors who scatter once the bulldozers

217
00:08:56,046 --> 00:08:56,395
arrive.

218
00:08:56,395 --> 00:08:58,142
That, the dissent had warned,

219
00:08:58,142 --> 00:09:00,937
was the human cost the broad reading made

220
00:09:00,937 --> 00:09:02,335
easy to ignore .

221
00:09:02,730 --> 00:09:04,517
Susette Kelo's house, at least,

222
00:09:04,517 --> 00:09:04,874
survived.

223
00:09:04,874 --> 00:09:07,732
It was not destroyed — it was carefully

224
00:09:07,732 --> 00:09:10,233
taken apart and moved, piece by piece,

225
00:09:10,233 --> 00:09:13,091
to a new lot elsewhere in New London,

226
00:09:13,091 --> 00:09:15,949
where it stands today as a small monument

227
00:09:15,949 --> 00:09:17,378
to the fight .

228
00:09:17,378 --> 00:09:19,879
She does not live in it anymore.

229
00:09:20,275 --> 00:09:22,202
Kelo is still good law.

230
00:09:22,202 --> 00:09:24,899
The Supreme Court has never overturned it.

231
00:09:24,899 --> 00:09:27,983
What pushed back against it was not the

232
00:09:27,983 --> 00:09:30,680
Court but the country — the backlash,

233
00:09:30,680 --> 00:09:33,764
the state reforms, and the empty lot that

234
00:09:33,764 --> 00:09:36,847
made the human cost impossible to ignore .

235
00:09:37,242 --> 00:09:40,434
And that is the strange lesson of the

236
00:09:40,434 --> 00:09:40,833
case.

237
00:09:40,833 --> 00:09:44,025
The Constitution's limit — "for public use" —

238
00:09:44,025 --> 00:09:47,218
was read so broadly that it stopped doing

239
00:09:47,218 --> 00:09:48,016
much work.

240
00:09:48,016 --> 00:09:51,208
What replaced it was not a better legal

241
00:09:51,208 --> 00:09:54,001
rule, but public outrage and an embarrassing

242
00:09:54,001 --> 00:09:55,597
failure on the ground.

243
00:09:55,992 --> 00:09:58,879
We have now followed the state as it

244
00:09:58,879 --> 00:10:01,044
reaches for your body, your phone,

245
00:10:01,044 --> 00:10:03,931
your movements, your property, and your home —

246
00:10:03,931 --> 00:10:06,817
the things it can watch and the things

247
00:10:06,817 --> 00:10:07,900
it can take.

248
00:10:07,900 --> 00:10:10,786
But there is one more kind of power,

249
00:10:10,786 --> 00:10:13,673
and it is the most personal of all.

250
00:10:13,673 --> 00:10:16,560
Not what the government can take from you,

251
00:10:16,560 --> 00:10:19,446
but what it can stop you from saying.

252
00:10:19,446 --> 00:10:21,972
The next case begins with a teenager,

253
00:10:21,972 --> 00:10:24,859
a few words, and a question every student

254
00:10:24,859 --> 00:10:27,384
and worker eventually asks: where does your

255
00:10:27,384 --> 00:10:29,189
right to speak actually end?

256
00:10:29,584 --> 00:10:31,000
That is next time.
